# YAML templates — chart-review-build

Full file templates written during Phase 2 (drafting). Use the `Write` tool
once per file with the full content populated from Phase 1 answers.

## `meta.yaml`

```yaml
# <task_id> — chart-review guideline (draft)
task_id: <task_id>
task_type: phenotype_validation     # or cohort_classification
review_unit: patient                # or encounter / episode
# Lifecycle: draft → calibrated → locked.
# The skill loader reads this field to gate LOCK-only actions.
# Set to "draft" when authoring; promote flips it to "locked".
status: draft
manual_version: 0.1.0-draft
index_anchor: index_date
output_shape: <outcome-first | evidence-first | timeline | hybrid | narrative>
overview_prose: |
  <2-3 paragraph synthesis of what the chart review answers>
denominator: "<who is in scope>"
index_event: "<the anchor event, e.g. 'MI hospitalization discharge'>"
time_windows:
  - id: <name_kebab>
    label: "<human description, e.g. '30 days post discharge'>"
final_output: <criterion_id_for_main_outcome>
```

## `criteria/<id>.yaml` (one per criterion)

```yaml
id: <id>
prompt: "<one sentence question>"
answer_schema:
  enum: [yes, no, no_info]          # or type: boolean / type: [number, "null"]
cardinality: one
time_window: <id_from_meta.time_windows>   # optional
group: <group_label>                       # optional
is_applicable_when: <DSL expression>       # optional gate
derivation: <DSL expression>               # optional, for derived fields
extraction_guidance: |
  <2-4 sentences on where to look in the chart>
guidance_prose:
  definition: <1-3 sentences>
  # PREFERRED — split prose into the four axes below. Each is a string
  # (typically a bullet list); reviewers and downstream tooling
  # (chart-review-improve, calibration) consume them as separate axes.
  satisfying_examples: |
    - "<positive example>" → answer
    - "<another positive example>" → answer
  non_satisfying_examples: |
    - "<negative example>" → other answer
    - "<another negative example>" → other answer
  boundary_examples: |
    - "<ambiguous case>" → <disambiguation rule>
  failure_modes: |
    - <common authoring or reviewer mistake to watch for>
  # LEGACY — single examples blob. Still parses for backward compatibility,
  # but new criteria should use the four-axis split above. Don't mix the
  # two forms in the same criterion; pick one.
  # examples: |
  #   - "<positive example>" → answer
  #   - "<negative example>" → other answer
```

The four-axis split is the lift-B convention (see
`skills/chart-review/references/atomic-criteria.md` and the disposition
spec). Failure modes are first-class authoring information — they
prevent the most common abstraction errors and give
`chart-review-improve` clean targets when proposing edits.

## `code_sets/<id>.yaml` (only when reviewer has supplied codes)

```yaml
id: <id>
codes:
  - <code>
  - <code>
source: reviewer-supplied
```

## `keyword_sets/<id>.yaml` (only when reviewer has supplied keywords / synonyms)

```yaml
id: <id>
keywords:
  - <phrase>
  - <phrase>
source: reviewer-supplied
```

## `edge_cases.yaml` (only when reviewer has flagged edge cases)

```yaml
edge_cases:
  - id: edge_1
    why: "<description of the edge case>"
    correct_answer_hint: "<what answer this case should produce>"
```
